{"questionId":"25682","questionHtml":"<p>Find the values of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi></math> for which the graph of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>g</mi></math> is concave-up.</p>","markschemeHtml":"<p>recognizing that for&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>g</mi></math> to be concave up,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>g</mi><mo>''</mo><mo>&gt;</mo><mn>0</mn></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<strong><em>(M1)</em></strong></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>g</mi><mo>''</mo><mo>&gt;</mo><mn>0</mn></math>&nbsp;when&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>f</mi><mo>'</mo><mo>&gt;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>4</mn><mi>x</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>12</mn><mo>&gt;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>&gt;</mo><mn>0</mn></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>(R1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi><mo>&gt;</mo><mn>3</mn></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><em><strong>[3 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"25682","referenceCode":"22M.1.SL.TZ2.7e","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"Find the values of x for which the graph of g is concave-up.","paper":"1","level":"SL","questionNumber":"e","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 3]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 5 —Calculus","Topic 5 —Calculus","SL 5.8—Testing for max and min, optimisation. Points of inflexion"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}}}